events.originalText: American journalist Daniel Pearl was kidnapped and later murdered by al-Qaeda agents in Karachi, Pakistan.
events.subtitle: Daniel Pearl
events.headline: American journalist Daniel Pearl kidnapped and murdered by al-Qaeda agents in Karachi, Pakistan

events.originalText: Five people attempted to set themselves on fire in Tiananmen Square, Beijing, an act that many later claimed to have been staged by the Chinese Communist Party to frame Falun Gong and thus escalate their persecution.
events.subtitle: Tiananmen Square self-immolation incident
events.headline: Five people attempt self-immolation in Tiananmen Square, Beijing

events.originalText: Madeleine Albright was sworn in as the first female United States Secretary of State, becoming the highest-ranking woman in the history of the U.S. government at that time.
events.subtitle: Madeleine Albright
events.headline: Madeleine Albright sworn in as first female United States Secretary of State

events.originalText: The first version of Mosaic, created by Marc Andreessen and Eric Bina, was released, becoming the first popular web browser.
events.subtitle: Mosaic (web browser)
events.headline: First version of Mosaic web browser released by Marc Andreessen and Eric Bina

events.originalText: USS Pueblo was seized by North Korean forces, who claimed that it had violated their territorial waters while spying.
events.subtitle: USS Pueblo (AGER-2)
events.headline: USS Pueblo seized by North Korean forces

events.originalText: The English new town of Milton Keynes was founded in Buckinghamshire, incorporating four towns and fifteen villages as well as planned new developments on intervening farmland.
events.subtitle: Planned community
events.headline: Milton Keynes founded in Buckinghamshire, England

events.originalText: American inventor Fred Morrison sold the rights to his "flying disc" to the Wham-O toy company, who later renamed it the "Frisbee" (example pictured).
events.subtitle: Walter Frederick Morrison
events.headline: Fred Morrison sells rights to 'flying disc' to Wham-O toy company

events.originalText: World War II: Japan began an invasion of the island of New Britain in the Australian Territory of New Guinea.
events.subtitle: World War II
events.headline: Japan invades New Britain in Australian Territory of New Guinea

events.originalText: Rebels led by John Chilembwe attacked local plantation owners, beginning an uprising regarded as a key moment in the history of Malawi.
events.subtitle: John Chilembwe
events.headline: Rebels led by John Chilembwe attack plantation owners in Malawi

events.originalText: Two men committed an armed robbery in Tottenham, London, and led police on a two-hour chase, partially by tram, that ended in the perpetrators' suicides.
events.subtitle: Tottenham Outrage
events.headline: Armed robbery in Tottenham, London ends in perpetrators' suicides

events.originalText: In the most fatal recorded mountaineering accident, 199 of the 210 members of an Imperial Japanese Army unit perished in a blizzard on the Hakkōda Mountains.
events.subtitle: Imperial Japanese Army
events.headline: Imperial Japanese Army unit perishes in mountaineering accident on Hakkōda Mountains

events.originalText: American Indian Wars: The United States Army massacred a friendly band of Piegan Blackfeet in the Montana Territory, resulting in about 200 deaths.
events.subtitle: American Indian Wars
events.headline: United States Army massacres friendly band of Piegan Blackfeet in Montana Territory

events.originalText: Elizabeth Blackwell (pictured) graduated from Geneva Medical College in New York, making her the first woman to receive a medical degree in the United States.
events.subtitle: Elizabeth Blackwell
events.headline: Elizabeth Blackwell graduates from Geneva Medical College

events.originalText: The Russian Empire and the Kingdom of Prussia partitioned the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth for the second time.
events.subtitle: Russian Empire
events.headline: Russian Empire and Kingdom of Prussia partition Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth

events.originalText: Bishop John Carroll purchased a plot of land that would become the home of the future Georgetown University, the oldest Catholic university in the United States.
events.subtitle: John Carroll (archbishop)
events.headline: Bishop John Carroll purchases land for future Georgetown University

events.originalText: James Hamilton killed James Stewart, 1st Earl of Moray, in the first recorded assassination of a head of government using a firearm.
events.subtitle: James Hamilton (assassin)
events.headline: James Hamilton kills James Stewart, 1st Earl of Moray

events.originalText: One of the deadliest earthquakes in history struck Shaanxi, China, resulting in at least 100,000 direct deaths.
events.subtitle: 1556 Shaanxi earthquake
events.headline: Deadly earthquake strikes Shaanxi, China

events.originalText: King Louis IX of France issued the Mise of Amiens, a settlement between King Henry III of England and barons led by Simon de Montfort heavily favouring the former, which later led to the Second Barons' War.
events.subtitle: Louis IX of France
events.headline: King Louis IX of France issues Mise of Amiens settlement
